      "widgets_values": [
        "Ukiyo-e English Bulldog face, portrayed as Lord Protector of the Western Provinces. Bulldog with a white and reddish-brown coat, a brachycephalic face, and droopy ears. It is dressed in Intricate blue and gold brocade kimono with layered white silk under-robes, secured with a wide, deep-purple obi. A small, ornate katana is nestled within the folds of the obi. Wears a lacquered eboshi hat adorned with a single golden crane.. It is Seated cross-legged on a plush, indigo zabuton cushion, the English Bulldog meticulously polishes the blade of a tanto with a silken cloth held in its paws. Head slightly bowed in concentration, the setting sun catches the subtle curve of the blade.. Beside it rest polished tanto blade and silken polishing cloth. The scene takes place Within a dimly lit chamber of a hilltop castle. The walls are adorned with faded gold-leaf panels depicting scenes of cherry blossoms in the moonlight. A low table sits nearby, bearing a sake set and a small bonsai tree. Tatami mats cover the floor. Sliding shoji screens filter the late afternoon light.. Soft, warm light filtering through shoji screens, creating long shadows. The scene is further illuminated by a single, flickering candle on the low table, casting dancing highlights on the polished blade and the Bulldog's fur. The mood feels Intimate, noble, relaxed, and atmospheric. A sense of quiet contemplation and understated power permeates the scene.. Ukiyo-e style, Japanese woodblock print aesthetic, flat bold outlines, traditional Edo-period color palette, woodblock carving texture, stylized natural forms, decorative patterned fabrics, flowing linear detail, Japanese woodcut print, Hiroshige and Hokusai influenced, hand-printed feel. No text, no watermark, no logos, no blur, no anatomical errors, no extra limbs"
      ]
    }
